Return to the very American ideal of labor rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have introduced legislation to establish union organization as a civil right.
"Just as unions die, so do middle-class jobs," said Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat and vice chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
That's why I'm proud to present the Employee Empowerment Act together with civil rights icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal options for discrimination because of trade union organisation as for other forms of discrimination - and thus stops anti-union forces.
Supplementing the National Labour Law to provide an opportunity for workers exposed to discrimination to organise trade union representation, to seek justice in a civil court - and to obtain damages or fines - is a sensible and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the other sponsors of their bill are proposing is to link back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks unions have faced in recent years—in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country—Americans once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand, and uphold labor rights.
There was a time millions of Americans remember when that country mentioned democracy, free speech, freedom of the press, and the right to organize in the same breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to adopt a constitution to ensure that Hedki Tojo's militarized autocracy would be replaced by democracy.
Fully aware of the role played by workers and their unions in the creation of a new Japan, they used language that explicitly recognized that "workers' rights to unification and collective bargaining and action are guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Acknowledging the fact that workers would have to organize and raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans inserted a clause that explicitly stated: "The right to form associations to secure and improve working and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and to every profession or trade.
Agreements which restrict or seek to reduce this right shall be null and void; Measures aimed at this are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights as adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global treaty, Roosevelt and the other authors included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to form or join trade unions to protect his interests."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to shape civil and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to form a union—and for that union to participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with corporations and government agencies—must be protected.
Indeed, after these rights have come under attack in America, it is very wise to recall the American ideal that working people must have the right to unite and make their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the workers' movement did not limit the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the living standards of millions of people, labor has miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and so should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of citizens' rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of workers' representation - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that made America great in the past and delivered on the promise of democracy.
Judge temporarily stops law that could force all abortion clinics in Louisiana to close
A U.S. federal judge on Sunday temporarily halted the implementation of a law in Louisiana that lawyers say would likely have led to the closure of all five abortion clinics in the state.
This measure, billed by Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal in June and set to go into effect Sept. 1, would force doctors performing abortions to purchase a patient admission right to a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge's decision means that for the time being, doctors can continue to legally perform abortions while requesting such a right.
"Plaintiffs may continue to operate in accordance with the law while seeking to obtain these rights," Federal Judge John deGravelles wrote in his ruling.
Within one month, a hearing for the judge is scheduled to bring about a more permanent decision on the law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of rulings against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to gain hospitalization rights.
"Today's decision means that women in Louisiana are escaping an insidious law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights," said Nancy Northup, president and chair of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which sued on behalf of three of the state's five clinics to stop the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the verdict also extended to the doctors from the two clinics who had not joined the lawsuit and had also applied for admission rights.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have enacted similar laws, with courts recently declaring such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of a Texas law that would have forced most of the hospitals remaining in the state to close were stopped by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates and the American College of Ostretricians and Gynecologists, as well as the American Medical Association, agree that physicians' admission rights require unnecessary restrictions.
Abortion opponents counter that the measures serve to protect women's health, although some also welcomed the effects of closing clinics.
Only one doctor performing abortions in Louisiana has patient admission rights, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all the rest of the doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, that doctor would stop performing the surgery out of fear for his safety, the group said.
Arguing against the ruling, Louisiana state officials said they would not punish doctors for performing abortions while their applications for patient admission rights were still pending.
Delayed diagnoses and lack of access to the best treatment options lead to higher death rates from ovarian cancer in rural areas.
Angelina Jolie and her brother James have posted a video tribute online to their mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women in Australia's rural areas are at a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than urban women.
Researchers analyzed the medical data of more than 1100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005 and found that only 25 percent were still alive five years after diagnosis.
Research lead Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Medical Research Institute said that for those living in rural and remote regions of the state, the risk of mortality during the study was 20 percent higher than for those living in urban areas.
SMALL STUDY: New Drugs Could Slow Lung and Ovarian Cancer
The researchers examined the medical care of the women over seven years.
Dr. Jordan said a woman's age at diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, existing pre-existing conditions, and social and economic status also affected survival chances.
Older women and those whose cancer was more advanced at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in rural and remote regions of the state, the risk of mortality during the study was 20 percent higher than for those in urban areas.
Although the study did not examine why women living outside the city were more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suspects delayed diagnosis and lack of access to the best treatment centers as possible factors for this.
"This disease is best treated by gynecologic oncologists, and these are mostly found in larger cities," she said.
Despite the improvement of telemedicine services to counter distances, she suggested as a possible remedy an increase in the service of flown in doctors to give specialists the opportunity to care for women closer to where they live, as well as treatment programs for people outside their region.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographic status, the study found poor long-term survival rates among women with ovarian cancer, highlighting the need for better treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer Cancer, is published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
In March 2013, Elisha Neave, a young mother of 33 from the Gold Coast, learned she had an aggressive form of ovarian cancer.
