Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure the battery compartment and other compartments are tightly closed.
Also set your camera to the photos or videos you want to take.
Some cameras and camcorders have scene and shooting modes that optimize the exposure time for the dim underwater conditions.
And before you jump in, check to what depth your equipment is functional.
Some cameras are only approved for up to 5 feet, others up to 50 or 60 feet.
Look for digital cameras for conventional and waterproof models in our buyer's guide and reviews.
Take multiple shots - because many will not work.
Point-and-shoot cameras have an LCD that allows you to compose images, but action cams usually don't.
Even if you have an LCD, it's difficult to watch underwater, and the right image setting is a matter of luck.
So you take a lot of shots.
If your camera has a series mode that takes a series of shots with slightly different exposure settings, use it.
Stay close to the surface.
The light gets dramatically worse the farther you move away from the surface.
So, if possible, stay close to the surface when shooting in a pool, lake, or ocean.
This will also allow you to add more color to your photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Get close to the objects.
This is also good advice on land, but it is all the more important underwater because of the poor lighting conditions.
It's especially important if you're working with an action cam: these devices often have a fixed wide-angle lens, which means you'll need to get closer to your objects if you want them to fill the entire frame.
