The Frontinus company contrasted the water and energy supply then and now, and Managing Director Petra Fricke knew: "We still benefit from the knowledge of that time".
This is also confirmed by graduate surveyor Ralph Heiliger from the "IngenieurteamZwei" from Rheinbach, who presented Roman surveying instruments such as Chorobat, Groma or Dioptra.
The Roman villa in Blankenheim presented sketches and models from the excavations in 1894 as well as bricks from the original hypocaust, the warm air heating that once heated the Roman villa.
