Genetic disorder often misdiagnosed
A British woman says she thought she was going to die as a result of a misdiagnosis for many years.
Karin Rodgers lived almost her entire youth believing that she had only a few years to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
She actually suffered from Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT) — a group of inherited disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spinal cord.
Charity CMT UK shared that misdiagnosis is a common problem in people with CMT because so little is known about the condition.
About 23,000 people in the UK are believed to suffer from CMT, which can lead to motor disorders such as muscle weakness, an unsteady gait and curved toes.
Sufferers also suffer from numbness or pain. The disease is incurable and progressive, which means that symptoms get worse over time.
When Rodgers was 13, she believed she was suffering from Friedreich's ataxia (FA) — a disease with very poor chances of survival.
Rodgers thought she would be in a wheelchair before she turned 18 and die before her 30th birthday.
The mother of two, who is now 51, said: "As a child, I knew I couldn't do the same thing as the others.
I kept falling down and everything took me longer.
I could never roller skate or skateboard with the other children and was often teased at school for my way of walking and running.
Rodgers said that at age 13, after several surgeries to relieve her Achilles tendons and stretch her feet, she looked at her medical record when her doctor left the room and read that she was suffering from FA.
"I felt guilty for being curious, so I didn't tell anyone, but I went home, looked for the illness in the library and wrote to the FA society," she said.
When I received an answer, I was shocked and panicked terribly.
I thought that I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die at 25, slowly losing all my abilities in between.
I did it all on my own and planned my own funeral.
She said when she turned 17, she realized that her abilities hadn't declined as much as she had imagined and consulted her doctor.
He just stood up and hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have, otherwise you'd be in a wheelchair right now."
I think you have something far less life-threatening.
After some genetic tests, she was diagnosed with CMT.
