Tax burden on business people in the Washington area increases with economic recovery
An economic recovery means more customers, more sales, and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
State and local corporate tax assessments in the country rose slightly last year, while economic recovery accelerated, according to a newly released study last week, and firms in the Washington area were no exception.
Companies in the District, Maryland and Virginia region collectively paid $27.6 billion to state and local entities in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from 2012 revenues of $26.6 billion.
The state and local corporate tax burden rose 4.3 percent to $671 billion last year, up from 3.9 percent the year before, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after several years of declining notices in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes rose more than local taxes, by 4.3 percent, according to the study, which was conducted by services agency Ernst & Young with the Center for State Taxation, a tax policy group.
More than half of the district's tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from corporate taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland's revenue comes from corporations.
Virginia has the lowest corporate tax revenue at 28 percent.
Much of the increase in tax revenue is due to a recovery in corporate property values, the researchers say, leading to a 3.7 percent increase in property taxes this year after three consecutive years of growth rates of less than 1 percent.
While much of that profit came from large states like California, New York, and Texas, the process seems to apply to the Washington area as well.
Companies in the District, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid over $10 billion in state and local real estate taxes last year, up from $9.6 billion in 2012 — a 4.2 percent increase over the course of a year.
But the apparent recovery in real estate values in Maryland is not as effective at increasing state and local tax revenues, where real estate taxes amount to just over one-fifth of corporate tax assessments.
Companies in Virginia and D.C. pay nearly half of their state and local taxes in the form of real estate taxes.
"Here's what happens in Maryland: a large portion of real estate, particularly in the D.C. tax jurisdiction, is either owned by the government or by nonprofits that don't pay real estate taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
Maryland is therefore forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, to provide the same services that other states offer.
The recent recovery in corporate tax revenues cannot be attributed solely to the recovery of the housing market
Business revenues also appear to be recovering, according to the data.
Businesses in the region reported income taxes on state organizations of $2.3 billion, compared to $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the highest amount in the region.
While the trend is in the same direction, the local tax burden on businesses is not rising evenly in all three places.
The increase rate in the district was in line with the national average at 4.3 percent, while the increase in Maryland was significantly higher, 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia reported below-average tax revenue of 4.1 percent.
Virginia has the significantly lowest corporate income taxes at 6 percent in all three departments (all three have fixed corporate tax rates).
The corporate tax rate is 8.25 percent in Maryland and a relatively high 9.975 percent in the district.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year showed that Virginia charges lower state and local corporate taxes and has a better overall tax climate than Maryland.
In the study, the district was not examined.
Despite the advantages, Virginia is under pressure from its southern neighbor.
North Carolina has passed legislation to cut its corporate tax rates from 6.9 percent to 6 percent this year, the same rate as Virginia, and the rate will fall to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its income targets next year, this law could reduce the state's corporate income tax rate to 3 percent by 2017.
