Amazon buys Twitch for $1.04 billion
AMAZON just confirmed what information reported Monday morning: The online retailer -- and video producer, and a host of other things -- is buying video streaming service Twitch for $1.04 billion ($970 million).
The announcement comes as a surprise, not because no one expected a Twitch acquisition, but because it was widely suspected that YouTube would acquire the company.
Three months ago, it looked like selling Twitch to Google's video service for a cool billion was a done deal, and the collaboration seemed natural.
Twitch, which was founded as a Justin.tv just three years ago, had launched as a general streaming service — a live version of YouTube.
Instead, it quickly became a platform for gamers who wanted to publish their bravura pieces in games, a "YouTube for live games," according to an insider.
The Twitch interface.
And "let's play", a video genre in which know-it-alls give the (mostly older) games a veneer of secret science theater, are already very popular on YouTube.
It's just that YouTube is often mentioned when describing Twitch, so the news that YouTube wanted to buy Twitch was received a bit bored, a textbook example of an established tech company buying up a potential competitor.
It's a mystery why the deal with YouTube didn't materialize, as the company was reportedly willing to pay as much as Amazon.
All we know right now is this statement from Emmet Shear, president of Twitch: "We chose Amazon because they believe in our community, they share our values and long-term visions, and they want to help us get there faster."
Another secret, frankly, is the incredible success of Twitch.
For snobs like me, who say they'd rather exercise than watch, it's hard to comprehend the attraction of watching others play rather than picking up the control console.
It's one thing to look over a friend's shoulder at 3 a.m. as she creeps through Resident Evil, and quite another to watch a weirdo get shot in the head 20 times in a row in Call of Duty.
All these games you could be watching right now.
Another problem is that many of the most popular games today are first-person games, so watching without your own control over your gaze perspective can be a really good recipe for headaches.
I admit that the fast-forward in which the Roger Bannisters of our electronic age complete entire games in record time are entertaining.
But unless there's a game or humor virtuoso around, his Twitch channel probably isn't that interesting.
But what do skeptics like me know about it?
Twitch is visited by 55 million unique visitors per month and is the fourth largest source of Internet traffic spikes.
And how exactly does Amazon want to make money out of it?
It's hard to imagine Twitch integrating with Amazon Instant Video as elegantly as YouTube could have swallowed Twitch.
But Twitch has something every company would like to have: thousands of young men being courted as advertisers.
As Twitch Chairman Shear said, Amazon and Twitch "both believe in the future of gaming," and the medium is showing no signs of shrinking, not even — gulp — as a spectator sport.
