Under this treetop there is peace
We showed a mighty trunk in our puzzle task of the summer series "Mein Stück vom Rhöner Glück" last Friday.
Several of these giant trees still exist in the district, the specimen pictured is the "Geißruheiche" above Unterweißenbrunn.
A bumpy footpath leads up to the approximately 600-year-old oak tree.
It goes past paddocks, basalt piles and basalt stone seas.
A little below the quarry of the Bauersberg, one kilometre north of the road to Weisbach, there it stands.
The natural monument looks vital, it rises above the other trees in the area and is reminiscent of an American sequoia with a circumference of over eight meters.
A small Buddha on a tree stump indicates that it is a spiritual or mystical place.
But despite intensive research, there were only clues to the origin of the name.
Dr. Wolfgang Schneider consulted the Bischofsheim archive and interviewed older people from Unterweißenbrunn to find out what significance it has with the Geißruheiche.
The result of his research remained the rather sober explanation for the name.
According to this, until about 80 years ago, the goatherds are said to have driven their animals from Unterweißenbrunn to the laboriously cleared and stone-freed meadows.
At the foot of the tree, the animal keepers, exhausted from the ascent, are said to have rested.
In the meantime, the area has regained its importance, because herds of goats are actually grazing on the meadows again.
The area has also been declared the core zone of the biosphere reserve, Schneider has further discovered.
When entering the stone accumulations, however, you should exercise caution, because the basalt warmed up by the sun is also a popular place for vipers.
A hiking trail leads from Unterweißenbrunn to the tree, which is somewhat hidden.
Further paths are signposted, which climb up towards the Hochrhön and invite you to an extended hike.
Where is the moated castle?
However, a moated castle, which is sought for our next task, is rather rare to find at altitude.
The reflection in the moat already gives a good impression of the building, but we have some historical buildings in the district to which the building portrait could fit.
Where is our "piece of Rhöner Glück"?
My piece of Rhön happiness
As with previous Main-Post series in previous years, there are prizes to be won again this year if they have the right solution.
If you like to take pictures yourself, you can also participate.
Under the e-mail address red.neustadt@mainpost.de you can send us the solution and also your very personal "piece of Rhöner happiness" under this keyword.
The most beautiful photos will be published.
After weeks of tug-of-war, Italy's Prime Minister and current EU President, Matteo Renzi, pushed through the nomination of his Foreign Minister Federica Mogherini as head of EU foreign policy against strong conservative resistance at the EU special summit last week, succeeding Britain's Catherine Ashton.
As the pro-government daily La Repubblica reports, Renzi sees the appointment of Mogherini, who is also regarded as the favourite in the government team, as strengthening the position of the Social Democrats and his own in the EU.
He also expects this to boost his "reform package" in Italy.
Last but not least, Renzi hopes to pacify the left-wing party base, which repeatedly revolts against him, because Mogherini is assigned to this - albeit in a rather moderate way.
According to the prevailing opinion in Rome, a political balance will be achieved vis-à-vis the conservative representatives with Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker and the Polish nominee Donald Tusk, who has been nominated for the Council of Nations.
Because the chief diplomat of the EU will also be deputy to Commission President Juncker.
The pending approval of the EU Parliament is considered certain.
Otherwise, President Giorgio Napolitano would hardly have called the nomination of the 41-year-old politician of the ruling Democratic Party (PD) an "important recognition" of Italy's role in the EU.
La Repubblica spreads optimism that Mogherini, who has been proven in leading party offices for almost two decades and is known for her ambition, will rise to the "enormous challenges".
Born in Rome, she is married and has two daughters.
The doctor of political science began her party career in 1996 in the youth organization of the then Democratici di Sinistra (Left Democrats), which merged with the Catholic Centre Party Margherita in 2008 to form today's social democratic PD.
In 1999, Mogherini became vice-president of the European Community Organisation of Socialist Youth for three years.
With the election in 2001 to the party council of the Left Democrats, she entered high party politics, worked in the foreign policy department, of which she soon became head.
It occupied traditional focal points of Italian foreign policy such as the Middle East, became known through studies on the NATO mission in Afghanistan, in which Italy is involved with a troop contingent, cultivated contacts with the Social Democrats in Europe and with the Democrats in the USA.
Since 2008 she has been a member of the Chamber of Deputies, where she is an expert on defence and European and international affairs.
When Renzi became prime minister in February 2014, he appointed Mogherini as his foreign minister.
If the PD today has a better relationship with the strong peace movement in the country, which contributed to the party's more than 40 percent vote in the EU elections in May, then Federica Mogherini has a share in it, as is noted in PD circles.
The accusations in Brussels that the new EU foreign policy chief has too little diplomatic experience, i.e. lacks substance, are countered in the PD.
In Brussels, especially by Poland and the Baltic members, Mogherini's suspiciously realistic accents on the crisis in Ukraine are pursued and defamed as a "Russia-friendly course".
It supports the South Stream pipeline, operated by the Russian company Gazprom, which is intended to transport Russian natural gas directly to southern Europe, bypassing Ukraine, which also serves to secure Italy's energy supply.
After Renzi began his term as EU president in July, Mogherini travelled to Moscow for her first state visit.
Photos showing her shake-hands with Putin were met with outrage in Brussels, as was the fact that she invited the Kremlin chief to a Milan economic summit in October.
