The Socialists in France should "shut up and put France in order," said François Hollande's most important ally.
Mr Valls called on the deeply divided left to show "its love" for the controversial socialist president, whose cabinet reshuffle has met with disapproval from the vast majority of French people.
The President deserves everyone's respect, he deserves our loyalty, he deserves our support.
"It is our duty to stay by his side," he said to great applause.
As a reassuring gesture, the prime minister insisted that his government would not challenge France's controversial 35-hour week, despite strong calls for a relaxation of the regulation by Emmanuel Macron, the new economy minister.
On Saturday, Mr Hollande urged his fellow socialists to show themselves "united" with the government.
But Christiane Taubira, the justice minister, threw a spanner in the works by appearing at a meeting of renegade socialist MPs and criticizing the Socialist Party for taking away the French people's "faith in their future."
Marine Le Pen, the far-right leader of the National Front, ridiculed the Socialists' constant trench warfare and said she could not imagine the new Valls government holding out for more than a few months.
François Hollande is the emperor without clothes, but Prince Manuel Valls doesn't have one either, they are forced to form a new government if the old one hasn't even survived a summer.
"And the new one will not survive the autumn or winter either," Miss Le Pen told supporters.
She reiterated her party's call for a dissolution of parliament, saying she was confident of winning early elections and was ready to govern.
France's ruling party suffered a defeat in local elections in March and the right-wing National Front came out on top in May's EU elections.
A poll in the Sunday Journal du Dimanche found that 76 percent of French people believe the Socialist Party is at risk of disintegrating into several rival factions before Hollande's term ends in 2017.
Pascal Perrineau, a political scientist at Sciences Po University, warned that the French would quickly lose patience if the new socialist government did not improve the economy and record unemployment.
"There is a small window of opportunity, but public opinion needs to feel quickly that things are changing," he warned.
Otherwise, the situation could deteriorate further.
Norwegian Cruise close to $3 billion deal with Prestige Cruises
Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings Ltd. NCHL. O, the world's third-largest cruise operator, is conducting advanced negotiations to acquire rival Prestige Cruises International Inc for about $3 billion, according to industry insiders.
A deal would give Norwegian Cruise, a $6.8 billion company, access to Prestige Cruises' luxury cruise ships as well as its wealthy clientele, while it would compete with larger rivals such as Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd (RCL. N) and Carnival Corp (CCL.N).
An agreement could be announced as early as this week, the sources said on Sunday, warning that the talks could also end inconclusively.
The owner of Prestige Cruises, private equity firm Apollo Global Management LLC (APO. N) also owns a 20 percent stake in Norwegian Cruise.
The sources asked to remain anonymous as the negotiations were not public.
Representatives for Norwegian Cruise and Prestige Cruises did not respond to requests for comment, while a spokesperson for Apollo declined to comment.
Miami-based Norwegian Cruise operates 13 cruise ships on routes between North America, the Mediterranean, the Baltic, Central America and the Caribbean.
Its revenues in 2013 were $2.57 billion, an increase of 13 percent compared to 2012.
Prestige Cruises, also based in Miami, operates under the brand names Oceania and Regent, which together operate eight cruise ships on routes to Scandinavia, Russia, the Mediterranean, North America, Asia, Africa and South America.
It reported revenue for 2013 of $1.2 billion, an increase of 6 percent over the previous year.
The cruise industry totals about $29 billion and is expected to grow in the next few years due to the strengthening of the middle class in emerging markets such as China and India.
Companies are trying to position themselves as the best choice among cruise operators for these new customers.
Prestige Cruises filed for an IPO with U.S. regulators in January 2014.
Apollo has been the majority shareholder in the company since an $850 million deal in 2007.
Norwegian Cruise in its current form was formed in 2000 through a merger with a cruise operator owned by Genting Bhd (GENT.KL), a leisure and casino conglomerate controlled by Malaysian billionaire Lim Kok Thay.
Apollo invested $1 billion in Norwegian Cruise in 2008.
Norwegian Cruise went public in January 2013.
Genting held 28 percent of the shares at the end of June, Apollo 20 percent of the shares and private equity firm TPG Capital LP an 8 percent stake in the company.
Carnival, Royal Caribbean Cruises and Norwegian Cruise collectively own 82 percent of passenger capacity on U.S. cruise ships, according to the original application documents for Prestige Cruises' IPO.
