Putin calls on Kiev to start "statehood talks" with eastern Ukraine
According to Russian media reports, Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded on Sunday that the Ukrainian government stop fighting against the separatists in the east of the country and immediately begin negotiations on the "statehood" of the breakaway region.
His spokesman, Dmitry Peskov, later clarified that Putin did not mean that the separatist-controlled area of eastern Ukraine would become part of Russia, but that his status vis-à-vis Ukraine needed to be redefined to give the Russian-speaking region the power to defend his rights and interests.
Putin's call for the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal footing with the pro-Russian insurgents, however, fits in with the strategy he has apparently pursued since the riots began five months ago: helping the separatists capture territory and putting pressure on the Ukrainian government to give the newly proclaimed region of Novorussia de facto independence for an alliance with Russia rather than with the West.
In an interview with state TV channel Kanal Eins, Putin condemned Ukraine's military campaign to retake separatist-held territories in the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which was seized in March and April after Moscow annexed Ukraine's Crimean peninsula on March 18.
The Kremlin and separatists have recently referred to the captured territory as "Novorossiya" or "Novorossiya," a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary heyday of the Russian empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who are hoping for early peace talks in the wake of Ukrainian politicians' campaigns for the Oct. 26 elections and while government groups are attacking civilian communities in separatist-held areas are "trapped in their illusions," Itar-Tass reported.
"We must immediately start detailed talks, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the state status of southeastern Ukraine, in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there," he said.
Peskov said Putin's reference to statehood must be seen in the context of the greater autonomy that has been discussed for months by the Kiev leadership to allay fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are threatened.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the necessary autonomy to the eastern regions, Peskov said.
This is not about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, "because this is not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but about an internal conflict in Ukraine."
The Kremlin spokesman's clarification to correct the "misinterpretation" of Putin's remarks underscored Russia's claim to leadership in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the east, as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, where the majority of the 2 million residents are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulty annexing the Donetsk and Luhansk regions in eastern Ukraine, as most of its 6.5 million inhabitants are not Russians and pre-conflict polls showed a broad majority in favor of remaining in Ukraine.
The autonomy, raised by Russian diplomats at international forums, would give Ukraine's regional governments the power to negotiate their own trade agreements and foreign relations, giving the Kremlin de facto control over an area linking Russian territory to Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, annexed five months ago, is the home port for most of Russia's navy, as well as an important commercial port and historic coastal region.
The region between the Rostov region in Russia and Crimea is also rich in mines, factories and foundries that produce important components for the Russian military.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko, in his inauguration speech on 7th June suggested that Ukrainian legislation - after new elections - should consider amendments to the constitution that give the respective territories greater control over their finances and the status of languages.
But his idea of autonomy seems to stand in sharp contrast to that of the Kremlin and the separatist rebels, whom Moscow is accused of arming and inciting.
Putin's latest call for Kiev to negotiate on an equal footing with separatist leaders came after another rebel advance last week after Russian troops and tanks entered eastern Ukraine via the previously peaceful region along the Sea of Azov.
The Russian-backed separatists took control of Novoazovsk in a coup that Ukrainian security officials fear is the first step in a campaign to take over the strategic coastal region as far as Crimea.
For this reason, massive civilian and military preparations have begun to fortify Mariupol, a steel industrial port of 500,000 inhabitants located between Novoazovsk and the narrow entrance to the Crimean peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at a meeting of EU leaders in Brussels on Saturday, urging action to prevent further Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
"We are on the verge of a point of no return," Poroshenko warned.
Thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks are now on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit did not decide on any concrete actions, the leadership demanded the draft of further sanctions against Russia, which should come into force in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukraine crisis.
Ukrainian soldiers were forced to withdraw from their positions in Ilovaisk after two Russian columns of tanks and 1,000 troops entered the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists, Colonel Andriy Lysenko, spokesman for Ukraine's National Security and Defense Council, told reports in Kiev on Saturday.
The first presumably 63 Ukrainian soldiers trapped by the Russian incursion in Ilovaisk were exchanged on Sunday for 10 Russian paratroopers captured on Ukrainian territory a week ago, Lysenko said on Sunday.
